  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does moratorium underwriting actually work?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">With moratorium, you don't complete a health questionnaire. Instead, any condition you've had symptoms, treatment, or advice for in the past 5 years is automatically excluded. After 2 consecutive years without any related treatment, symptoms, or medical advice for that condition, it becomes covered. The catch: you don't know exactly what's excluded until you file a claim.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Should I choose moratorium or full medical underwriting?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Choose moratorium if you have pre-existing conditions and want a path to eventual coverage, or if you want quick approval without health questions. Choose full medical underwriting if you want certainty about what's covered upfront, or if you're healthy and want clean coverage from day one.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why isn't Allianz available in Germany?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Allianz SE is a German company, and Germany has specific regulations requiring local health insurance for residents. Allianz Care is designed for international expats, not German domestic coverage. German residents need German domestic insurance (like TK, AOK, or private German plans).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why are customer reviews mixed?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most complaints relate to claims disputes, especially around pre-existing condition interpretations and "medical necessity" denials. Allianz is a large insurer with many policies—some experiences are excellent, others frustrating. Document everything and understand your policy before you need to use it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I cancel my policy mid-year?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. After the initial 30-day cooling off period, Allianz Care policies run for the full policy year. You can't cancel mid-year unless you have specific qualifying life events. This is standard for annual health insurance but worth knowing before you commit.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the 60% deductible savings work?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Allianz offers deductible options from €0 to €10,000. The €10,000 deductible saves approximately 60% on premiums compared to €0 deductible. This is higher than most competitors. It works well for healthy individuals who rarely hit their deductible—you keep the premium savings.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="verdict">Our Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Allianz Care is the best choice for expats with pre-existing conditions who want a realistic path to coverage.</strong> The moratorium underwriting option is rare and genuinely valuable. Combined with the largest provider network (2M+) and aggressive deductible discounts (up to 60%), Allianz offers unique value.
  </p>
  <p>
    However, mixed customer reviews mean you should go in with realistic expectations. Document everything, understand your policy, and be prepared to advocate for yourself if you have claims disputes. The moratorium also means uncertainty until you actually file a claim.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bottom line:</strong> For pre-existing conditions or budget-conscious expats wanting the largest network, Allianz is hard to beat. For those prioritizing customer service or mental health coverage, look elsewhere.
  </p>

